snippet.textDisplay:
Hi Jeff, I have been watching your videos for some years now, and I wanted to ask if you can tell us more about the impacts of Alcohol consumption. 
I returned to the gym a month ago, after having a very long break. During this break, I picked up some bad habits. Regular drinking (almost 4-5 standard drinks a day, and it's my taste for wine). I gained 17 pounds also. In the last month, I returned to eating clean, and currently dropped the 17 pounds. However, I feel lighter, I feel more energetic. At the same time, my reading tells me how much damage alcohol does to the test and oestrogen levels on a male.

Drinking never effected my work, life in a personal way, as I don't drink to a stage I black out (ever) but still enjoyed the red wine. Last 3 days I have not had a drink, I feel fine and actually happier lol. And off course the REM sleep is helping me get up at 5am and hit the gym 4-5 days a week. Now if you could help us understand the effects, of lets say one drink a week, or at a social event, how much is too much and the volume? Or in all together, no drinks even once per week and keep it social? Im sure it will help many off us here following you. Thanks Jeff.

As always, great video, Jeff!
I also have a question/video idea: in your bloated abs video you mentioned that we should not stop squeezing our abs when exhaling during the concentric part. I've been working out for a while and when I started developing a regulated breathing technique I figured that the way it "works" for me is to always inhale when doing the concentric part, so quite the opposite of what you are saying. Am I doing it completely wrong? Could you maybe cover breathing in an upcoming video? I would love to hear the differences between inhaling at concentric vs eccentric, pros and cons. Also interested in how we should breathe when doing symmetric exercises (e.g. bicycles, mountain climbers). Should we breathe in when going left and breathe out when going right (or vice-versa) or breathe in when we go left (or right) and breathe out when we go to that side again?
Thank you, and keep up the good work! Cheers!
